1.nameOriginDescription: Fushigidane may be a combination of 不思議 fushigi (strange; mysterious) and 種 tane (seed), as well as a pun of the phrase 不思議だね Fushigi da ne? ("Isn't it strange?").

2.nameOriginDescription: Fushigisou may be a combination of 不思議 fushigi (strange; mysterious) and 草 sō (grass), as well as a pun of the phrase 不思議そう Fushigi sō ("It seems strange").

3.nameOriginDescription: Fushigibana may be a combination of 不思議 fushigi (strange; mysterious) and 花 hana (flower).

4.nameOriginDescription: Hitokage may be a combination of 火 hi (fire) and 蜥蜴 tokage (lizard), forming together the word 火蜥蜴 hitokage (mythical salamander).

5.nameOriginDescription: Charmeleon may be a combination of char (to burn) and chameleon .  Lizardo may be derived from the transcription of the English word lizard .

6.nameOriginDescription: Charizard may be a combination of char (to burn) and lizard .  Lizardon may be a combination of lizard and either dragon or -don (common suffix in dinosaur names derived from the Ancient Greek word for tooth).

7.nameOriginDescription: Zenigame may be a combination of 銭 zeni (money) and 亀 kame (turtle), forming the word 銭亀 zenigame (baby Japanese pond turtle ). According to Pokémon Black and White 's television program PokéQuiz , "'Zeni' is an old-fashioned word for money. Squirtle's shells look like old coins, so that's how they got their name!"

8.nameOriginDescription: Kameil may be a combination of 亀 kame (turtle, tortoise) and tail .

9.nameOriginDescription: Kamex may be a combination of 亀 kame (tortoise, turtle) and マックス makkusu (max; maximum).

10.nameOriginDescription: Caterpie may be a corruption, or shortening, of caterpillar .

11.nameOriginDescription: Transel may be a combination of transform and cell or possibly a pun on ランドセル randoseru (school bag).

12.nameOriginDescription: Butterfree may be a combination of butterfly and free . It may also involve パタパタ patapata (the sound of wings flapping) and 振る furu (to flap).

13.nameOriginDescription: Weedle may be a combination of worm and needle .  Beedle may be a combination of bee and needle .

14.nameOriginDescription: Kakuna may be a corruption of cocoon .  Cocoon is literally cocoon .

15.nameOriginDescription: Spear is literally spear . It may also be derived from アピス Apis (the genus name of the honey bee) spelled backwards.

16.nameOriginDescription: Poppo may be derived from ぽっぽ poppo (onomatopoetic sound of a pigeon's coo).

17.nameOriginDescription: Pidgeotto may be a combination of pigeon and the Italian diminutive suffix -otto . It is also very similar to the romanized spelling of Pidgeot 's Japanese name, ピジョット pijotto .

18.nameOriginDescription: Pidgeot and Pigeot may be a combination of pigeon and jet (referring to its speedy flight).

19.nameOriginDescription: Koratta may be a combination of 子 ko (child) or 小 ko (small) and rat .

20.nameOriginDescription: Ratta may be derived from ラット ratto (rat).

21.nameOriginDescription: Onisuzume may be a combination of 鬼 oni (ogre) and 雀 suzume (sparrow).

22.nameOriginDescription: Onidrill may be a combination of 鬼 oni (demon), 鳥 tori (bird), and ドリル doriru (drill).

23.nameOriginDescription: The Japanese name Arbo (アーボ) may be derived from cobra , or boa (ボア) spelled backwards.

24.nameOriginDescription: Arbok is cobra spelled backwards, but with the c replaced with a k . [ 1 ]

25.nameOriginDescription: Pikachu is a combination of ピカピカ pikapika (onomatopoeia for sparkle) and チューチュー chūchū (the sound of a mouse squeaking). [ 1 ] [ 2 ]

26.nameOriginDescription: Raichu may be a combination of 雷 rai (thunder) and チューチュー chūchū (onomatopoeia for the squeak of a mouse).

27.nameOriginDescription: Sandshrew may be a combination of sand and shrew .  Sand is simply sand .

28.nameOriginDescription: Sandslash may be a combination of sand and slash .  Sandpan may be a combination of sand and pangolin .

29.nameOriginDescription: Nidoran♀ may be derived from needle , with ♀ as an indication of its female gender. It may also involve 二度 nido (twice).

30.nameOriginDescription: Nidorina may be a combination of needle , rhinoceros , and -ina (feminine diminutive suffix in Spanish and Italian). It may also involve 二度 nido (twice).

31.nameOriginDescription: Nidoqueen may be a combination of needle and queen . It may also involve 二度 nido (twice).

32.nameOriginDescription: Nidoran♂ may be derived from needle , with ♂ as an indication of its male gender. It may also involve 二度 nido (twice).

33.nameOriginDescription: Nidorino may be a combination of needle , rhinoceros , and -ino (masculine diminutive suffix in Spanish and Italian). It may also involve 二度 nido (twice).

34.nameOriginDescription: Nidoking may be a combination of needle and king . It may also involve 二度 nido (twice).

35.nameOriginDescription: Clefairy may be a combination of clef (musical symbol) and fairy .  Pippi may be derived from the repetition of the first syllable of pixie .

36.nameOriginDescription: Clefable may be a combination of clef (musical symbol) and fable .  Pixy may be derived from pixie .

37.nameOriginDescription: Rokon may be a combination of 六 roku (six), こん kon (onomatopoetic sound of a fox's cry), and 焜炉 konro ( gas stove ). It may also involve 恨 kon (grudge; from the curse its Evolution may cast on its foes).

38.nameOriginDescription: Kyukon may be a combination of 九 kyū (nine) or 九尾狐 kyūbiko ( nine-tailed fox ) and こん kon (onomatopoetic sound of a fox's cry). It may also involve 旧恨 kyūkon (old grudge) and 焜炉 konro ( gas stove ).

39.nameOriginDescription: Purin may refer to プリン purin (pudding; referring to its soft body). It may also involve プチ puchi (petite) and pretty .

40.nameOriginDescription: Pukurin may be a combination of ぷくぷく pukupuku (cute and chubby), ぷりぷり puripuri (angrily or in a huff; referring to its personality), くりくり kurikuri (big and round), and プリン purin (pudding; referring to its soft body). It may also involve 風船 fūsen (balloon) and 膨れる fukureru (to become inflated).

41.nameOriginDescription: Zubat may be a combination of bat and ずばっと zubatto (piercingly).

42.nameOriginDescription: Golbat may be a combination of gore , ghoul , or gulp and bat .

43.nameOriginDescription: Nazonokusa may be a play on 謎の草 nazo no kusa (enigmatic herb).

44.nameOriginDescription: Kusaihana may be derived from 臭い花 kusai hana (stinking flower).

45.nameOriginDescription: Vileplume may be a combination of vile and plume (object that resembles a feather; cloud of dispersed substance) or bloom .  Ruffresia may be derived from Rafflesia .

46.nameOriginDescription: Paras may be derived from parasite , referring to the parasitic mushroom growing on its back.

47.nameOriginDescription: Parasect may be a combination of parasite and insect .

48.nameOriginDescription: Kongpang may be derived from compound eye (visual organ found in insects) or 昆虫 konchū (insect).

49.nameOriginDescription: Venomoth may be a combination of venom and moth .  Morphon may be derived from metamorphosis or the butterfly genus Morpho .

50.nameOriginDescription: Diglett may be a combination of dig and the suffix -let (indicating small size).  Digda may be derived from dig .

51.nameOriginDescription: Dugtrio may be a combination of dug and trio (a group of three).

52.nameOriginDescription: Nyarth may be a play on ニャー nyā (the Japanese onomatopoeia for the sound a cat makes).

53.nameOriginDescription: Persian may refer to Persian cats or possibly Persian leopards . It could also be related to purr , the onomatopoeia for the noise a cat makes when content.

54.nameOriginDescription: Koduck may be a combination of 小 ko (small) or 子 ko (child) and duck .

55.nameOriginDescription: Golduck may be a combination of gold and duck . While Golduck itself is not colored gold, gold is often used to symbolize psychic abilities e.g., the Gold Gummi is the Gummi variety loved by Psychic-type Pokémon, and the Marsh Badge 's Japanese name is "Gold Badge".

56.nameOriginDescription: Mankey may be a combination of man and monkey . It may also involve mad and cranky .

57.nameOriginDescription: Okorizaru may be derived from 怒り猿 okorizaru (angry monkey).

58.nameOriginDescription: Growlithe may be a combination of growl and lithe (flexible).  Gardie may refer to its abilities as a guard dog, as a corruption of guard or guardian .

59.nameOriginDescription: Arcanine may be a combination of arcane and canine .  Windie may refer to wind or windy , reflecting its defining nature of being fast like the wind, further emphasized by Extreme Speed being its signature move in Generation II .

60.nameOriginDescription: Nyoromo may be a combination of ニョロニョロ nyoronyoro (onomatopoeia for wriggling) and 子供 kodomo (child).

61.nameOriginDescription: Nyorozo may be a combination of ニョロニョロ nyoronyoro (onomatopoeia for wriggling) and 小僧 kozō (youngster).

62.nameOriginDescription: Nyorobon may be a combination of ニョロニョロ nyoronyoro (onomatopoeia for wriggling) and 坊 bon (boy).

63.nameOriginDescription: Abra may be derived from abracadabra , an incantation used in stage magic .  Casey may be named after Edgar Cayce , a purported psychic famous for entering self-induced trances.

64.nameOriginDescription: Kadabra may be derived from abracadabra , an incantation used in stage magic .  Yungerer may be named after Uri Geller , an illusionist famed for his spoon-bending technique. This contributed to Geller suing Nintendo for using his likeness in a character.

65.nameOriginDescription: Alakazam's name is derived from alakazam , an incantation used in stage magic similar to abracadabra .  Foodin may be named after Harry Houdini , a famed illusionist and escape artist.

66.nameOriginDescription: Wanriky is derived from 腕 wan (arm) and 力 riki (strength); [ 2 ] altogether, it is derived from an alternate reading of 腕力 wanryoku (arm strength, physical strength).

67.nameOriginDescription: Goriky may be derived from 剛力 gōriki (herculean strength).

68.nameOriginDescription: Kairiky may be derived from 怪力 kairiki (superhuman strength), which is the name of its category in Japanese.

69.nameOriginDescription: Madatsubomi may be derived from まだ蕾 mada tsubomi (still in bud).

70.nameOriginDescription: Utsudon may be derived from 靫葛 utsubokazura (pitcher plant).

71.nameOriginDescription: Utsubot may be derived from 靫葛 utsubokazura (pitcher plant) and possibly ポット pot .

72.nameOriginDescription: Menokurage may be a combination of 目の敵 me no kataki (enemy) or 目の毒 me no doku (temptation, literally "poison to the eye") and 水母 kurage ( jellyfish ).

73.nameOriginDescription: Dokukurage may be a combination of 毒 doku (poison) and 水母 kurage ( jellyfish ).

74.nameOriginDescription: Isitsubute is a combination of 石 ishi (stone) and 礫 tsubute (throwing stones). [ 2 ]

75.nameOriginDescription: Golone may be a combination of ゴロンゴロン goron-goron (onomatopoeia of rolling rocks) and stone .

76.nameOriginDescription: Golonya may be a combination of ゴロンゴロン goron-goron (onomatopoeia of rolling rocks) and montagna (Italian for mountain ).

77.nameOriginDescription: Ponyta may be a combination of pony and bonita ( pretty in various Iberian languages).

78.nameOriginDescription: Rapidash may be a combination of rapid and dash (referring to the high speed at which it runs) or ash (referencing its Fire type).  Gallop is literally gallop , a form of running for hooved animals.

79.nameOriginDescription: Yadon may be a combination of 宿借り yadokari ( hermit crab ), 宿主 yadonushi (parasitic host), and 鈍 don (dull). It may also be a shortening of ヤドラン Yadoran , Slowbro 's Japanese name.

80.nameOriginDescription: Yadoran may involve 宿借り yadokari ( hermit crab ), 宿主 yadonushi (parasitic host), and 鈍 don (dull). According to Yugoslavian singer-songwriter Jadranka Stojaković , Yadoran was named after her first name (transliterated as ヤドランカ Yadoranka in Japanese). Stojaković had worked for Konami during her residence in Japan, and a former colleague of hers who later joined Game Freak brought her name to mind while naming Yadoran. [ 1 ]

81.nameOriginDescription: Magnemite may be derived from magnetite (a mineral with magnetic properties) or a combination of magnet and mite (minute object).  Coil may refer to electromagnetic coil .

82.nameOriginDescription: Magneton may be derived from magneton (various units of magnetic moment) or possibly magnetron (high-power vacuum tube).  Rarecoil may be a combination of rare-earth magnet and electromagnetic coil .

83.nameOriginDescription: Kamonegi may be a combination of 鴨 kamo (duck) and 葱 negi ( spring onion ) that forms the expression 鴨葱 kamo negi , an abbreviation of the proverb 「鴨が葱を背負って来る」 kamo ga negi o shottekuru (literally "a duck comes bearing spring onions") that means "easy target" or "golden opportunity".

84.nameOriginDescription: Doduo may be a combination of dodo (an extinct, flightless bird) and duo (a pair).  Dodo is literally dodo .

85.nameOriginDescription: Dodorio may be a combination of ドードー dodo , 鳥 tori (bird), and トリオ trio .

86.nameOriginDescription: Seel is derived from seal .  Pawou may be derived from an onomatopoeia of a seal's bark.

87.nameOriginDescription: Jugon may be derived from 儒艮 jugon (dugong).

88.nameOriginDescription: Betbeter may be derived from べとべと betobeto and べたべた betabeta , both meaning sticky.

89.nameOriginDescription: Betbeton may be derived from べとべと betobeto (sticky) and ton .

90.nameOriginDescription: Shellder may be derived from shell and possibly shelter .

91.nameOriginDescription: Parshen may be a combination of パール pearl and シェル shell .

92.nameOriginDescription: Gastly may be a combination of gas , ghost , and ghastly (frightful).  Ghos may be derived from ghost and gas .

93.nameOriginDescription: Haunter may be derived from haunt and the agentive suffix -er or possibly hunter .  Ghost is literally ghost .

94.nameOriginDescription: Gengar and Gangar may be derived from Doppelgänger (ghostly double of a living person). It may also involve 幻 gen (phantasm).

95.nameOriginDescription: Iwark may be a combination of 岩 iwa (rock) and either ブルワーク bulwark or スネーク snake .

96.nameOriginDescription: Drowzee may be a combination of drowsy and zzz (onomatopoeia for snoring).  Sleepe may be derived from sleep .

97.nameOriginDescription: Hypno may be derived from hypnosis .  Sleeper is literally sleeper .

98.nameOriginDescription: Krabby may be a combination of crab and crabby (grouchy or ill-tempered).  Crab is literally crab .

99.nameOriginDescription: Kingler may be a combination of king crab and angler . It may also involve fiddler crab .

100.nameOriginDescription: Biriridama may be a combination of ビリビリ biribiri (sound of electric shock) and 玉 tama (sphere).

101.nameOriginDescription: Marumine may be a combination of 丸 maru (circle) and mine , as in landmine .

102.nameOriginDescription: Tamatama may be derived from 玉子 tamago (egg), as well as being a play on 偶々 tamatama (unexpectedly).

103.nameOriginDescription: Nassy may be a combination of ココナッツ kokonattsu (coconuts) and 椰子 yashi (palm tree).

104.nameOriginDescription: Karakara may be derived from カラカラ karakara (onomatopoeia for light clattering), contrasting with the ガラガラ garagara (onomatopoeia for heavy clattering) in Marowak 's Japanese name.

105.nameOriginDescription: Garagara may be derived from ガラガラ garagara (onomatopoeia for heavy clattering), contrasting with the カラカラ karakara (onomatopoeia for light clattering) in Cubone 's Japanese name.

106.nameOriginDescription: Hitmonlee is named after Bruce Lee , [ 1 ] and may additionally involve a combination of hit and monster . The name is also related to Hitmonchan and Hitmontop , both of which are parallel Evolutions to it as of Generation II .  Sawamular may be derived from Tadashi Sawamura , a famous kickboxer.

107.nameOriginDescription: Hitmonchan is named after Jackie Chan , [ 1 ] and may additionally involve a combination of hit and monster . The name is also related to Tyrogue 's other Evolutions, Hitmonlee and Hitmontop .  Ebiwalar may be derived from the Japanese world champion boxer Hiroyuki Ebihara .

108.nameOriginDescription: Beroringa may be a combination of べろ bero (colloquial term for tongue), ベロリ berori (licking), ベロベロ berobero ( onomatopoeia for licking), and lingua (Latin for tongue).

109.nameOriginDescription: Dogars may be derived from 毒ガス doku-gasu (poison gas).

110.nameOriginDescription: Matadogas may come from 又 mata (again) and 毒ガス doku-gasu (poison gas). It may also be derived from マスタードガス masutādogasu ( mustard gas ).

111.nameOriginDescription: Sihorn may be a combination of 犀 sai (rhinoceros) and horn .

112.nameOriginDescription: Sidon may be a combination of 犀 sai (rhinoceros) and don .

113.nameOriginDescription: Chansey may be from either chance or chancy .  Lucky is literally lucky .

114.nameOriginDescription: Monjara may be a combination of monster , もじゃもじゃ mojamoja (shaggy or unkempt), and 毛むくじゃら kemukujara (densely covered in thick hair).

115.nameOriginDescription: Kangaskhan may be a combination of kangaroo and khan , possibly in reference to Genghis Khan .  Garura may be a combination of kangaroo and ruler .

116.nameOriginDescription: Tattu may be derived from 竜 tatsu (dragon) or 竜の落とし子 tatsu-no-otoshigo (seahorse, lit. "illegitimate child of a dragon").

117.nameOriginDescription: Seadra may be a combination of sea , seahorse , dragon , seadragon (a type of animal related to seahorses), and Hydra (a mythological water creature).

118.nameOriginDescription: Tosakinto may be derived from 土佐金 tosakin (curly fantail goldfish), a distinctive breed of goldfish.

119.nameOriginDescription: Azumao may be derived from 東錦 azuma nishiki (a breed of goldfish) and 王 ō (king).

120.nameOriginDescription: Hitodeman may be a combination of 海星 hitode (starfish) and man (possibly in reference to Ultraman ).

121.nameOriginDescription: Starmie may be a combinaton of star and mystery . Its name in English may also involve me (in opposition to the you in Staryu ).

122.nameOriginDescription: Mr. Mime is an abbreviation of Mister and mime .  Barrierd may be a combination of barrier (referring to the invisible walls it can create) and weird .

123.nameOriginDescription: Scyther may be a combination of scythe and the suffix -er (something that does an action).  Strike is literally strike .

124.nameOriginDescription: Jynx may be a corruption of jinx , a curse or hex of bad luck.  Rougela may be derived from rouge , a type of makeup and also the French word for red , and also from the French verb geler (to freeze, to be freezing cold).

125.nameOriginDescription: Eleboo may be a combination of electric or エレキ eleki (electric) and ブンブン bunbun (buzz).

126.nameOriginDescription: Magmar may be a combination of magma and fulmar (a seabird known for projectile-vomiting stomach oil as a defense mechanism).  Boober may be a combination of booby (another type of seabird) and a corruption of burn .

127.nameOriginDescription: Kailios may be a combination of the Greek letter Χ (カイ kai ), 刈 kai (shear), 魁偉 kaii (brawny), cross (referring to its scissor-like horns ), and κοριός korios ( Greek for bug ).

128.nameOriginDescription: Tauros may be derived from its Japanese name, Kentauros. It may also be derived from ταῦρος tauros (Greek for bull).  Kentauros may be derived from Κένταυρος Kéntauros (Greek for centaur ).

129.nameOriginDescription: Koiking may be a combination of 鯉 koi (carp) and king , which may come from 金魚 Kingyo (goldfish).

130.nameOriginDescription: According to Ken Sugimori , Gyarados's name has no specific origin and was chosen merely for its "force". [ 1 ] However, it may be variously derived from 虐殺 gyakusatsu (slaughter), 逆境 gyakkyō (adversity), or 逆転 gyakuten (reversal, turnaround); 荒らす arasu (to devastate); and 脅す odosu (to threaten).

131.nameOriginDescription: Lapras may be derived from Laplace or lapis lazuli .  Laplace may be a reference to Pierre-Simon Laplace , a mathematician who wrote several books on the mathematical properties of the sea and tides. Alternatively, Laplace may be derived from la place (French for seat), referring to how passengers sit on its back like a seat to be ferried across bodies of water.

132.nameOriginDescription: Ditto is literally ditto (that which was stated before; copy of a document; imitation).  Metamon may be a combination of metamorphose (to undergo a physical transformation) or meta- (prefix meaning "encompassing" or "transcending", which may refer to Transform allowing Ditto to take on the shape of every other Pokémon) and monster .

133.nameOriginDescription: Eevee and Eievui are pronunciations of E-V , the first two letters in the word Evolution . [ 1 ]

134.nameOriginDescription: Vaporeon may be a combination of vapor and eon (an immeasurably long period of time, possibly referring to how long evolution takes naturally). Eon is a suffix all Eevee Evolutions share and was Eevee's English prototype name.  Showers is literally showers , referring to a bathroom shower or rain shower .

135.nameOriginDescription: Jolteon may be a combination of jolt and eon (an immeasurably long period of time, possibly referring to how long evolution takes naturally). Eon is a suffix all Eevee Evolutions share and was Eevee's English prototype name.  Thunders is literally thunders .

136.nameOriginDescription: Flareon may be a combination of flare and eon (an immeasurably long period of time, possibly referring to how long evolution takes naturally). Eon is a suffix all Eevee Evolutions share and was Eevee's English prototype name.  Booster is literally booster , possibly referring to the booster rocket .

137.nameOriginDescription: Porygon is derived from ポリゴン porigon ( polygon ).

138.nameOriginDescription: Omnite may be a combination of 鸚鵡貝 ōmugai ( nautilus ) and ammonite .

139.nameOriginDescription: Omstar may be a combination of 鸚鵡貝 ōmugai ( nautilus ) and star .

140.nameOriginDescription: Kabuto may be derived from 兜 kabuto (helmet) and 兜蟹 kabutogani ( horseshoe crab ).

141.nameOriginDescription: Kabutops may be derived from 兜蝦 kabutoebi ( Triops ), 兜 kabuto (helmet), Triops and -ops (common suffix in names of prehistoric animals derived from the Ancient Greek word for face).

142.nameOriginDescription: Aerodactyl may be a combination of ἀέρος aéros ( Greek for air ) or aeroplane, and pterodactyl .  Ptera may be derived from pterosaur or Pteranodon .

143.nameOriginDescription: Kabigon is derived from Kirby (Japanese: カービィ Kābī ), the eponymous main character of Nintendo 's Kirby video game series . In an interview with Game Informer, Junichi Masuda stated that Kōji Nishino, the main inspiration for Snorlax, used to be called "Kirby" as a nod to his large appetite. [ 3 ] Kabigon may also involve 黴 kabi (mold), noting the fact that Snorlax will eat anything, even moldy food.

144.nameOriginDescription: Articuno is a combination of arctic and uno (Spanish for one, indicating that it is the first of the Kanto legendary birds ). [ 1 ] [ 2 ]  Freezer is literally freezer (that which freezes).

145.nameOriginDescription: Zapdos is a combination of zap and dos (Spanish for two, indicating that it is the second in the series of Kanto legendary birds ). [ 1 ] [ 2 ]  Thunder is literally thunder .

146.nameOriginDescription: Moltres is a combination of molten and tres (Spanish for three, indicating that it is the third in the trio of Kanto legendary birds ). [ 1 ] [ 2 ] It may also derive from molt .  Fire is literally fire .

147.nameOriginDescription: Miniryu may be a combination of miniature and 竜 ryū (dragon).

148.nameOriginDescription: Hakuryū may be derived from 白竜 hakuryū (white dragon).

149.nameOriginDescription: Kairyu may be from 海竜 kairyū (sea dragon). It may also involve 怪獣 kaijū (monster), 快 kai (cheerful), and 破壊 hakai (destruction).

150.nameOriginDescription: Mewtwo may be a combination of Mew or mutant (ミュータント) and two .

151.nameOriginDescription: Mew may be a combination of mutant or mutation and new . It may also involve 妙 myō (wonderful, exquisite).

152.nameOriginDescription: Happa is the Japanese word 葉っぱ happa , meaning " leaf ".

153.nameOriginDescription: Bayleef and Bayleaf derive from bay leaf , a herb used in cooking known for its pungent smell.

154.nameOriginDescription: Meganium may be a combination of mega and geranium .

155.nameOriginDescription: Hinoarashi may be a combination of 火 hi (fire) and ヤマアラシ (山荒) yama-arashi ( porcupine ). It can be taken to mean 火の嵐 hi no arashi (storm of fire).

156.nameOriginDescription: Magmarashi may be a combination of magma, 穴熊 anaguma ( badger ) and 山荒 yama-arashi ( porcupine ).

157.nameOriginDescription: Bakphoon may be a combination of 爆風 bakufū (blast from an explosion) and typhoon .

158.nameOriginDescription: Waninoko may be taken to mean 鰐の子 wani no ko (child of a crocodile/ alligator ).

159.nameOriginDescription: Croconaw may be a combination of crocodile and gnaw , though it may also involve maw or jaw .  Alligates may be derived from alligator .

160.nameOriginDescription: Ordile may be a combination of 王 ō (king), 皇 ō (emperor), or 大 ō (large), and crocodile .

161.nameOriginDescription: Otachi may be a combination of 尾 o (tail) and 立ち tachi (stand) or 鼬 itachi (weasel).

162.nameOriginDescription: Ootachi may be a combination of 大 ō (big), 尾 o (tail), 立ち tachi (stand), and 鼬 itachi (weasel).

163.nameOriginDescription: Hoho is derived from ホー hō (the sound an owl makes). [ 2 ]

164.nameOriginDescription: Yorunozuku may be a combination of 夜 yoru (night) and 木菟 mimizuku ( horned owl ).

165.nameOriginDescription: Ledyba and Rediba may come from ladybug or ladybird and red .

166.nameOriginDescription: Ledian and Redian may be a combination of ladybug or ladybird , red , and possibly alien or guardian .

167.nameOriginDescription: Itomaru may be a combination of 糸 ito (thread) and 丸 maru (circle; suffix in young boy's names).

168.nameOriginDescription: Ariados may be named after Ariadne , a Cretan princess in Greek mythology associated with strings and mazes. In the myth, Ariadne gave Theseus a ball of twine before he entered the Labyrinth to slay the Minotaur, so that he may trail the strand behind him and find his route back to her. Ariados may also be a combination of arachnid (Latin for spider ) and 脅す odosu (to threaten) or dos (Spanish for two , used possibly because it has two stingers, or because it is the second form in its evolutionary line).

169.nameOriginDescription: Crobat may be a combination of cross and bat . It may also involve acrobat (referring to its agility in the air).

170.nameOriginDescription: Chinchou and Chonchie may be derived from 提灯 chōchin (lantern) or 提灯鮟鱇 chōchin-ankō ( footballfish ).

171.nameOriginDescription: Lanturn may be a combination of lantern and turn (as in "turn on the light").  Lantern is literally lantern .

334.nameOriginDescription: Tyltalis may be derived from チルット Tyltto ( Swablu ) and alis (Latin for wings). It may also be a reference to the play The Blue Bird (L'Oiseau bleu) by Belgian playwright Maurice Maeterlinck , featuring two siblings named Mytyl and Tyltyl tasked in finding the bluebird of happiness . The latter half of the name may be derived from cockatrice , a mythical creature with a draconic or serpentine body and a rooster's head. It may also involve チル chiru ( Ryukyuan for crane) or Tyl (alternate name of the star Epsilon Draconis , located in the constellation Draco) and Altais (former name of the star Delta Draconis, also located in the constellation Draco).

355.nameOriginDescription:
Yomawaru may be a combination of 妖魔 yōma ( ghost ), 悪 waru (bad thing), and 夜回り yomawari (night watch). 
It is also similar to 山童 Yamawaro , a hairy, one-eyed spirit that appeared in The Illustrated Night Parade of a Hundred Demons .

359.nameOriginDescription: Absol may be derived from absolute or absolution (setting free from guilt), as well as 危ない abunai (dangerous) and possibly 物騒 bussō (dangerous) or 恐る osoru (to fear). It may also be a combination of the Latin prefix ab- (away from) and sol (Latin for sun).

360.nameOriginDescription: Sohnano is homophonous with the phrase そうなの？ Sō na no? , which means "Really?" or "Is that so?" This plays off its Evolution, Wobbuffet , whose Japanese name of Sonans is homophonous with the interjection そうなんす Sō na-n-su , which roughly means, "That's the way it is." Together, they make for a potential perpetual conversation of, "Really?" followed by, "That's the way it is," and so on, as seen in Camp Pikachu .

361.nameOriginDescription: Yukiwarashi is literally 雪童子 yukiwarashi (either referring to the generic name for childlike snow spirits, or the homonym tale in the folklore of Niigata Prefecture) . It may also involve a combination of 雪 yuki (snow) and 座敷童子 zashiki-warashi or 童子 warashi (archaic word for child).

371.nameOriginDescription: Tatsubay may be a combination of 竜 tatsu (dragon) and baby .

374.nameOriginDescription: Beldum and Dumbber may be derived from dumbbell , a small weight used in weight training.

376.nameOriginDescription: Metagross may be a combination of metal and cross (referring to its facial feature), gross (referring to its weight of 1212 lbs., as a gross is 12×12), or groß (German for large ).

379.nameOriginDescription: Registeel may be a combination of regis (Latin for royal) and steel .

380.nameOriginDescription: Latias may be a combination of lateō (Latin for I conceal , I lie hidden ) and -as (Latin feminine suffix). It might also reference Eos (the Greek goddess of dawn) or Eos (a genus of parrots with red and blue plumage). It's possible that its name is derived from Plato 's dialogue Critias .

381.nameOriginDescription: Latios may be a combination of lateō (Latin for I conceal , I lie hidden ) and -os (Latin masculine suffix). It might also reference Eos (the Greek goddess of dawn) or Eos (a genus of parrots with red and blue plumage). It's possible that its name is derived from Plato 's dialogue Timaios .

382.nameOriginDescription: Kyogre is a combination of 海 kai (sea) or 海王 kaiō (king of the sea) and ogre . [ 1 ] It may also involve orca (killer whale).

383.nameOriginDescription: Groudon may be a combination of ground and don (Spanish for lord) or -don (common suffix in dinosaur names derived from the Ancient Greek word for tooth). It may also involve 土 do (earth) or ドン don (onomatopoeia for booming or crashing sound).

384.nameOriginDescription: Rayquaza may be derived from 裂空 rekkū (sky-rending), a word appearing in various media and merchandise that featured Rayquaza. The latter half may be derived from 座 za (seat), relating to compounds such as 星座 seiza (constellation) and 王座 ōza (throne). It may also involve רָקִיעַ rāqī́aʿ (Hebrew for firmament ), ray , and quasar .  Rayquaza's mikado organ refers to 帝 mikado (emperor), another name for the Emperor of Japan .

385.nameOriginDescription: Jirachi may be derived from желать zhelatʹ (Russian for to wish ). It may also involve jinn or 幸 sachi (Japanese for fortune).

386.nameOriginDescription: Deoxys is derived from deoxyribonucleic acid —or DNA —the medium of genetic code in cellular organisms. [ 1 ]

387.nameOriginDescription: Naetle may be a combination of 苗 nae ( sprout ) and turtle .

Tritodon may be a combination of Tritoniidae (family of shell-less marine gastropod molluscs) or Triton snail (marine gastropod mollusk named after Triton , Greek god of the sea), and don (Spanish for lord) or -don (common suffix in dinosaur names derived from the Ancient Greek word for tooth). It may also be derived from torito (Spanish for little bull).

424.nameOriginDescription: Eteboth may be a combination of 猿公 etekō (monkey), 得手 ete (strong point), and both .

445.nameOriginDescription: Gaburias may be a combination of がぶり gaburi (with a big bite) and carcharias or アース āsu (earth).

450.nameOriginDescription: Kabaldon may be a combination of 河馬 kaba (hippopotamus) and don .

468.nameOriginDescription: Togekiss may be a combination of 刺 toge (spike) and kiss , referencing its kind nature.

470.nameOriginDescription: Leafeon may be a combination of leaf and eon (an immeasurably long period of time, possibly referring to how long evolution takes naturally). Eon is a suffix all Eevee Evolutions share and was Eevee's English prototype name.  Leafia may be derived from leaf .

471.nameOriginDescription: Glaceon may be a combination of glacier (a large, slow-moving mass of ice on land) or glace (French for ice) and eon (an immeasurably long period of time, possibly referring to how long evolution takes naturally). Eon is a suffix all Eevee Evolutions share and was Eevee's English prototype name. Incidentally, its name is also an anagram of congeal (to become solid, usually by cooling).  Glacia may be derived from glacier . It may also involve grace .

472.nameOriginDescription: Gliscor and Glion may be combinations of glide and scorpion .

473.nameOriginDescription: Mammoo may be a combination of mammoth and ブーブー būbū ( onomatopoeia for oinking).

474.nameOriginDescription: Porygon-Z is a combination of Porygon and the letter Z . The latter may refer to the Z axis in a 3D coordinate system, or the fact that it is the final stage in its evolutionary line, with Z being the final letter of the Latin alphabet. Z could also be a corruption of the number 2 , referring to its status as a glitched Evolution of Porygon2 .

Emrit may be a combination of M of the acronym UMA (Unidentified Mysterious Animal, wasei-eigo for cryptid) and spirit .

492.nameOriginDescription: Shaymin is from 謝謝 xièxie (Chinese for thanks ). [ 1 ] It may also be derived from 蝟 harinezumi (hedgehog) and םשמי Shamayim (Hebrew for heaven ) with the latter correlating directly with Shaymin's Sky Forme.

493.nameOriginDescription: Arceus may be a combination of αρχή arkhé (Ancient Greek for origin and authority ) or alpha and deus (Latin for god ) or Zeus (king of the gods in Greek mythology). It may also involve arcane , aureus (Latin for golden), arc , arcesso (Latin for I summon ), Archeus (an aspect of the astral plane), or Chaos (the origin state of the universe in Greek mythology, often personified as the first primordial deity).

494.nameOriginDescription: Victini is derived from victory , [ 1 ] and also possibly destiny , teeny , or tiny .

495.nameOriginDescription: Tsutarja is a combination of 蔦 tsuta ( Japanese creeper ) and 蛇 ja (snake). [ 1 ]

496.nameOriginDescription: Janovy may be a combination of 蛇 ja ( snake ) and canopy or ivy .

497.nameOriginDescription: Jalorda may be a combination of 蛇 ja (snake) and lord .

498.nameOriginDescription: Pokabu may be a combination of ぽかぽか pokapoka (warm) and 豚 buta (pig) or ブー bū (oink).

499.nameOriginDescription: Chaoboo may be a combination of 超 chāo (Chinese for super) or 炒 chǎo (Chinese for stir-fry ) and 豚 buta (pig) or ブー bū (oink).

500.nameOriginDescription: Enbuoh may be a combination of 炎 en (flame), 豚 buta (pig), 武 bu (martial arts), ブー bū (oink), 王 ō (king), and possibly ember and boar .

501.nameOriginDescription: Mijumaru may be a combination of 水 mizu (water) or 未熟 mijuku (naive or immature) and 丸 maru (round; a common suffix in male Japanese names). According to Ken Sugimori, suffixes such as -maru or -suke were considered for Oshawott's Japanese name to make it sound more typically Japanese. [ 1 ] Miju may also refer to an otter named Mijbil , the subject of an autobiographical novel and movie called Ring of Bright Water .

502.nameOriginDescription: Futachimaru may be a combination of 二つ futatsu (two), 太刀 tachi (long sword), and 丸 maru (round; common suffix in male Japanese names).

503.nameOriginDescription: Daikenki may be a combination of 大 dai (great), 剣 ken (sword), 鬼 ki (demon), and 剣鬼 kenki (devilish swordsman).

504.nameOriginDescription: Minezumi may be a combination of 見 mi (looking) and 鼠 nezumi (mouse).

505.nameOriginDescription: Miruhog may be a combination of 見る miru (to observe) and groundhog .

506.nameOriginDescription: Lillipup may be a combination of lilliputian and pup .  Yorterrie may derive from Yorkshire terrier .

507.nameOriginDescription: Herdier and Herderrie may be a combination of herding dog and terrier .

508.nameOriginDescription: Mooland may be a combination of 尨犬 mukuinu (shaggy dog), ムチムチ muchimuchi (plump), and Newfoundland or Scotland .

509.nameOriginDescription: Choroneko may be a combination of ちょろまかす choromakasu (to pilfer) and 猫 neko (cat).

510.nameOriginDescription: Liepard may be a combination of lie and leopard .  Lepardas may be a combination of leopard and λεόπαρδος leopardós (Ancient Greek for leopard) or leopardus (Latin for leopard).

511.nameOriginDescription: Yanappu may be a combination of 柳 yanagi ( willow ), 野菜 yasai (vegetables), 菜 na (greens), and ape .

512.nameOriginDescription: Yanakkie may be a combination of 柳 yanagi ( willow ), 野菜 yasai (vegetables), 菜 na (greens), monkey , and possibly ヤンキー yankee (delinquent youth).

513.nameOriginDescription: Baoppu may be a combination of 爆 bào (Chinese for "to burst"; "to explode"), バースト bāsuto (burst), and ape .

514.nameOriginDescription: Baokkie may be a combination of 爆 bào (Chinese for "to burst"; "to explode"), バースト bāsuto (burst), and monkey .

515.nameOriginDescription: Hiyappu may be a combination of 冷や hiya (cool water) and ape .

516.nameOriginDescription: Hiyakkie may be a combination of 冷や hiya (cool water) and monkey .

517.nameOriginDescription: Munna may be a combination of 夢 mu (dream) and luna (Latin for moon). It may also involve mana , 花 hana (flower), muna (Finnish for egg), or むにゃむにゃ munya munya (Japanese onomatopoeia for indistinct mumbling, as if talking in one’s sleep ).

518.nameOriginDescription: Musharna may be a combination of ムシャムシャ mushamusha (onomatopoeia for eating), 夢 mu (dream), and luna (Latin for moon). It may also involve mana and 花 hana (flower).

519.nameOriginDescription: Mamepato may be a combination of 忠実 mame (diligent) or 豆 mame (prefix meaning tiny ) and 鳩 hato (pigeon).

520.nameOriginDescription: Hatoboh may be a combination of 鳩 hato (pigeon) and 坊 bō (boy, monk). It may also be derived from イーハトーヴ Ihatov (also spelled イーハトーヴォ/イーハトーボ Ihatovo ), a fictional ideal world mentioned in some of Kenji Miyazawa 's works. The Pokédex entries in Pokémon White , X and Omega Ruby say, "Many people believe that, deep in the forest where Tranquill live, there is a peaceful place where there is no war," which might be a reference to Miyazawa's utopia.

521.nameOriginDescription: Kenhallow may derive from ケンホロロ kenhororo (onomatopoeia of pheasant cries) and けんもほろろ ken-mo-hororo (curt or brusque).

522.nameOriginDescription: Shimama may be derived from 縞馬 shimauma (zebra).

523.nameOriginDescription: Zebraika may be a combination of zebra and 雷火 raika (flash of lightning).

524.nameOriginDescription: Dangoro may be a combination of 団子 dango (Japanese dumpling) and ゴロゴロ goro goro (onomatopoeia for the sound of a boulder rolling).

525.nameOriginDescription: Gantle may be a combination of 岩 gan (rock) and mantle .

526.nameOriginDescription: Gigaiath may be a combination of γίγας gigas , Γαῖα Gaia (the Greek goddess personifying the Earth ), and Goliath . It may also involve アース āsu (earth).

527.nameOriginDescription: Koromori may be a combination of 心 kokoro (heart) or  コロコロ korokoro (onomatopoeia for lightly rolling) and 蝙蝠 kōmori (bat).

528.nameOriginDescription: Kokoromori may be a combination of 心 kokoro (heart) and 蝙蝠 kōmori (bat).

529.nameOriginDescription: Mogurew may be a combination of もぐら mogura and どりゅう doryū , which are both possible readings of 土竜 (mole). It may also involve screw or shrew .

530.nameOriginDescription: Doryuzu may be a combination of ドリル doriru (drill), 土竜 doryū (mole), and 渦 uzu (spiral or swirl).

531.nameOriginDescription: Tabunne may be derived from a pun of 多分ね tabun ne (maybe) or 多聞 tabun (hearing many things). It may also involve 耳朶 mimitabu (earlobe).

532.nameOriginDescription: Dokkorer may be derived from どっこらしょ dokkorasho (heave-ho). It may also involve δοκάρι dokári (Greek for beam).

533.nameOriginDescription: Dotekkotsu may be a combination of 土木 doboku (engineering works) and 鉄骨 tekkotsu (steel frame).

534.nameOriginDescription: Roubushin may be a combination of 老 rō (old) and 武神 bushin (warlord) or 普請 fushin (construction work/public work).

535.nameOriginDescription: Otamaro may be a combination of お玉杓子 otamajakushi (tadpole; musical notes) and 麿 maro (affectionate suffix for young men) or 麻呂眉 maro-mayu (shaved eyebrows).

536.nameOriginDescription: Gamagaru may be derived from 蝦蟇 gamagaeru ( Japanese common toad ).

537.nameOriginDescription: Gamageroge may be a combination of 蟇 gama (toad) and ゲロゲロ gerogero (onomatopoeia for frog croaking).

538.nameOriginDescription: Nageki may be a combination of 投げる nageru (to throw), 撃 geki (strike), and 鬼 ki ( demon ).

539.nameOriginDescription: Dageki may be a combination of 打撃 dageki (blow, strike) and 鬼 ki ( demon ).

540.nameOriginDescription: Kurumiru may be derived from お包み okurumi (swaddle).

541.nameOriginDescription: Kurumayu may be a combination of 包まる kurumaru (to be wrapped) and 繭 mayu (cocoon).

542.nameOriginDescription: Hahakomori may be a combination of 葉 ha (leaf), 母 haha (mother), and 子守 komori (babysitting).

543.nameOriginDescription: Fushide may be a combination of 節 fushi (joint/segment) and 百足 mukade (centipede).

544.nameOriginDescription: Wheega may be a combination of wheel and 毬 iga (sphere).

545.nameOriginDescription: Scolipede may be a combination of Scolopendra (genus of centipedes ) and centipede or millipede .  Pendror may be derived from Scolopendra .

546.nameOriginDescription: Monmen may be derived from 木綿 momen (cotton).

547.nameOriginDescription: Elfuun may be a combination of elf and 風 fū (wind) or typhoon .

548.nameOriginDescription: Churine may be a combination of チューリップ chūrippu (tulip), 百合根 yurine (lily bulb), and 根 ne (root).

549.nameOriginDescription: Lilligant may be a combination of lily and elegant .  Dredear may be a combination of dress , dear , lady , and Dianthus .

550.nameOriginDescription: Bassrao may be a combination of bass and 丈夫 masurao (warrior, referring to its bold, violent nature ) or バカラオ bakarao ( bacalhau ).

551.nameOriginDescription: Meguroco may be a combination of 目黒 meguro (black-eyed) and crocodile .

552.nameOriginDescription: Waruvile may be a combination of 悪い warui (bad/evil/sinful), evil , crocodile , and possibly gavial .

553.nameOriginDescription: Waruvial may be a combination of 悪い warui (bad/evil) and gavial .

554.nameOriginDescription: Darumaka and Darumakka seem to be a combination of Daruma and 真赤 makka (crimson) or a corruption of macaque .

555.nameOriginDescription: Hihidaruma may be a combination of 火 hi (fire), 緋 hi (scarlet), 狒々 hihi (baboon), Daruma , and 火達磨 hidaruma (the state of being on fire).

556.nameOriginDescription: Maractus may be a combination of maraca and cactus .  Maracacchi may be a combination of maraca , cactus and mariachi .

557.nameOriginDescription: Ishizumai may be a combination of 石 ishi (stone) and 住まい sumai (dwelling).

558.nameOriginDescription: Iwapalace may be a combination of 岩 iwa (rock) and palace .

559.nameOriginDescription: Zuruggu may be derived from 狡 zuru (sly fellow), 狡い zurui (crafty), or ずるずる zuruzuru (onomatopoeia for dragging slowly).

560.nameOriginDescription: Zuruzukin may be a combination of 狡 zuru (sly fellow), 狡い zurui (crafty), or ずるずる zuruzuru (onomatopoeia for dragging slowly) and 頭巾 zukin (hood) or possibly skin .

561.nameOriginDescription: Sigilyph may be a combination of sigil and glyph . It may also draw its name from sylph , a mythological spirit of the air.  Symboler may be a combination of symbol and the agentive suffix -er . It may also involve bora (a type of wind) or Ra (the Ancient Egyptian falcon-headed sun god).

562.nameOriginDescription: Yamask may be a combination of 闇 yami (darkness), や ya (bad), or Yama (lord of the dead in Hindu and Buddhist mythology), and mask .  Desumasu may be a combination of death and mask . It may be a pun off of ですます体 desumasu-tai , a form of polite Japanese which gets its name from the fact that sentences often end in です desu or ます masu .

563.nameOriginDescription: Desukarn may be a combination of death and 棺 kan (coffin). It may also be a pun on です か desu ka , a form used at the end of an interrogative sentence which can be translated as "Is it?".

564.nameOriginDescription: Tirtouga may be a combination of turtle and a corruption of tortuga (Spanish for turtle or tortoise ).  Protoga may be a combination of Protostega and tortuga (Spanish for turtle or tortoise ).

565.nameOriginDescription: Abagoura may be a combination of 肋骨 abarabone (rib) and 甲羅 kōra (shell). It may also involve 暴れる abareru (to thrash or act violently).

566.nameOriginDescription: Archen may be derived from Archaeopteryx or the geological eon Archean .

567.nameOriginDescription: Archeops and Archeos may be derived from Archaeopteryx and -ops (common suffix in names of prehistoric animals derived from the Ancient Greek word for face). Archeops may also allude to Cheops , the Greek name for Egyptian pharaoh Khufu .

568.nameOriginDescription: Yabukuron may be a combination of 破く yabuku (to tear) or 破ける yabukeru (to get torn), ぶくぶく bukubuku (loose-fitting), and 袋 fukuro (bag).

569.nameOriginDescription: Dustdas may be a combination of ダスト dasuto (dust, trash, refuse) and 出す dasu (to take out).

570.nameOriginDescription: Zorua may be a combination of zorro (Spanish for fox) and rua (Irish for red, possibly referring to its red fur; madra rua is Irish for fox).

571.nameOriginDescription: Zoroark may be a combination of zorro (Spanish for fox ) and dark , 悪 aku (evil), or arch- (prefix for "top" or "chief").

572.nameOriginDescription: Minccino may be a combination of mini (referring to its miniature size), mink (an animal known for its fur and its use in women's clothing), or mint (pristine condition), and chinchilla or chino cloth . The suffix -ino or -cino is also a diminutive to denote something small.  Chillarmy may be a combination of chinchilla and charming .

573.nameOriginDescription: Cinccino and Chillaccino may be a combination of chinchilla and chino cloth . The suffix -ino or -cino is also a diminutive to denote something small.

574.nameOriginDescription: Gothimu may be a combination of Gothic and 予知夢 yochimu (precognitive dream).

575.nameOriginDescription: Gothimiru may be a combination of gothic and 見る miru (to see).

576.nameOriginDescription: Gothitelle may be a combination of Gothic and mademoiselle (French for the title of miss ), foretell , or stelle (Italian for stars ).  Gothiruselle may be a combination of Gothic and mademoiselle (French for the title of miss ).

577.nameOriginDescription: Uniran may be a combination of uni- (prefix meaning one , as in unicellular organism ) and 卵 ran (spawn). It may also refer to se unirán (Spanish for "they will join together"), as Solosis appears to be made of two parts.

578.nameOriginDescription: Doublan may be a combination of double and 卵 ran (spawn).

579.nameOriginDescription: Lanculus may be a combination of 卵 ran (spawn), and nucleus or homunculus .

580.nameOriginDescription: Koaruhie may be a combination of 子 ko (child) or 小 ko (small) and a corruption of 家鴨 ahiru (duck).

581.nameOriginDescription: Swanna is derived from swan and may be a combination of swan and ballerina .

582.nameOriginDescription: Vanillite may be a combination of vanilla and lite (reduced) or possibly delight , as well as stalactite .  Vanipeti may be a combination of vanilla and petit (French for small).

583.nameOriginDescription: Vanillish may be a combination of vanilla and delish (slang term for delicious).  Vanirich may be a combination of vanilla and rich .

584.nameOriginDescription: Baivanilla may be a combination of bi- (prefix meaning two) or 倍 bai (double) and vanilla .

585.nameOriginDescription: Shikijika may be a combination of 四季 shiki (four seasons) and 鹿 shika (deer).

586.nameOriginDescription: Mebukijika may be a combination of 芽吹き mebuki (to bud) and 鹿 shika (deer).

587.nameOriginDescription: Emolga may be a combination of 衣紋 emon (drapery) and モモンガ momonga ( flying squirrel ).

588.nameOriginDescription: Kaburumo may be derived from 蝸牛被 maimaikaburi ( Carabus blaptoides ) and 甲虫 kabutomushi (beetle).

589.nameOriginDescription: Escavalier may be a combination of escargot (French for snail) and cavalier (French for mounted soldier) or chevalier (French for knight), as well as pun of Excalibur .  Chevargo may be a combination of chevalier and escargot .

590.nameOriginDescription: Tamagetake may be a combination of 玉 tama (sphere), 魂消る tamageru (to be astonished), and 茸 take ( mushroom ).

591.nameOriginDescription: Morobareru is a combination of もろに moro ni (completely) and ばれる bareru (slang for "[for a secret] to be exposed"), referring to how it no longer convincingly looks like a Poké Ball . [ 1 ]

592.nameOriginDescription: Pururill may be a combination of プルプル purupuru (onomatopoeia for jiggling) and frill .

593.nameOriginDescription: Burungel may be a combination of ブルンブルン burunburun (onomatopoeia for shaking) and ゲル gel .

594.nameOriginDescription: Mamanbou may be a combination of mama and 翻車魚 manbō (ocean sunfish).

595.nameOriginDescription: Bachuru may be a combination of バチバチ bachibachi (onomatopoeia for electric crackling) and タランチュラ taranchura (tarantula). It may also involve bug and 虫 chū (bug).

596.nameOriginDescription: Dentula may be a combination of 電池 denchi (battery), 電柱 denchū (utility pole), 虫 chū (bug), and タランチュラ tarantula .

597.nameOriginDescription: Tesseed may be a combination of 鉄 tetsu (iron) and seed .

598.nameOriginDescription: Nutrey may be a combination of nut and 唖鈴 arei (dumbbell).

599.nameOriginDescription: Giaru may be derived from ギア gear .

600.nameOriginDescription: Gigiaru may be derived from ギア gear , with the first syllable repeated.

601.nameOriginDescription: Gigigiaru may be derived from ギア gear , with the first syllable repeated twice.

602.nameOriginDescription: Shibishirasu may be a combination of 痺れ shibire (numbness) or 痺鰻 shibire-unagi (electric eel) and 白子 shirasu ( whitebait ).

603.nameOriginDescription: Shibibeel may be a combination of 痺れ shibire (numbness) or 痺鰻 shibire-unagi (electric eel), ビリビリ biribiri (onomatopoeia for an electric shock), and eel .

604.nameOriginDescription: Shibirudon may be a combination of 痺れ shibire (numbness) or 痺鰻 shibire-unagi (electric eel) and don (Spanish for lord) or -don (common suffix in dinosaur names derived from the Ancient Greek word for tooth).

605.nameOriginDescription: Elgyem may be derived from the abbreviation LGM (little green men, a stereotypical depiction of extraterrestrials as diminutive green-skinned humanoids).  Ligray may be derived from little or little green men and greys (purported extraterrestrial beings depicted as diminutive gray-skinned humanoids).

606.nameOriginDescription: Ohbem may be a combination of 大 ō (large) and BEM (pronounced as a single word in Japanese).

607.nameOriginDescription: Hitomoshi may be derived from 火点し hi-tomoshi , which literally means "lighting a lamp" but can also refer to a person who leads a funeral procession with a torch. The name can also be interpreted as 人燃し hito-moshi (to burn a man to death).

608.nameOriginDescription: Lampent may be a combination of lamp , lambent (softly glowing), and possibly lament .  Lampler may be derived from lamp .

609.nameOriginDescription: Chandelure may be a combination of chandelier and lure .  Chandela may be a combination of chandelier and candela (Latin for candle) or candelabra .

610.nameOriginDescription: Kibago may be a combination of 牙 kiba (fang or tusk), 顎 ago (jaw), and dragon .

611.nameOriginDescription: Onondo may be a combination of 斧 ono (axe) dragon , and -don (common suffix in dinosaur names derived from the Ancient Greek word for tooth).

612.nameOriginDescription: Ononokus may be a combination of 斧 ono (axe), 戦く ononoku (to tremble), アックス akkusu (axe), and possibly -onychus (common suffix in dinosaur names derived from the Ancient Greek word for claw).

613.nameOriginDescription: Kumasyun may be a combination of 熊 kuma (bear) and くしゅん kushun (onomatopoeia of a sneeze). It may also incorporate 熊 xióng (Chinese for bear).

614.nameOriginDescription: Tunbear may be a combination of tundra , 氷柱 tsurara (icicle), and bear .

615.nameOriginDescription: Cryogonal may be a combination of cryo- (prefix for icy cold) and hexagonal .  Freegeo may be a combination of freeze or frigid and geometry .

616.nameOriginDescription: Chobomaki may be a combination of おちょぼ口 ochoboguchi (puckered-up mouth) and 巻貝 makigai (snail; conch).

617.nameOriginDescription: Accelgor may be a combination of accelerate and escargot (French for snail).  Agilder may be a combination of agile and rider .

618.nameOriginDescription: Maggyo may be a combination of マッド maddo (mud) and 魚 gyo (fish). It may also refer to まぐろ maguro (tuna).

619.nameOriginDescription: Kojofu may be a combination of オコジョ okojo (ermine) and kung fu .

620.nameOriginDescription: Kojondo may be a combination of オコジョ okojo (ermine) and 道 dō (teachings, path), commonly used in the name of many East Asian martial arts (such as judo or taekwondo )

621.nameOriginDescription: Crimgan may be a combination of crimson and dragon , 顔 gan (face), or 岩 gan (rock).

622.nameOriginDescription: Gobit may be a combination of golem and bit (small in size) or 小人 kobito (small person).

623.nameOriginDescription: Goloog may be a combination of golem and サイボーグ saibōgu (cyborg).

624.nameOriginDescription: Komatana may be a combination of 駒 koma (a piece in the board game Shogi ), 細切れ komagire (small pieces), and 刀 katana (sword) or 小刀 kogatana (knife).

625.nameOriginDescription: Kirikizan may be a combination of 切り刻む kirikizamu (to mince) and 斬 zan (to cut or slay).

626.nameOriginDescription: Bouffalant may be a combination of bouffant (puffy, round hairstyle) and buffalo .  Buffron may be a combination of buffalo , afro , and bison .

627.nameOriginDescription: Washibon may be a combination of 鷲 washi (eagle) and 坊 bon (boy, as a prefix or a nickname), ibon (Filipino for bird ), or haribon ( Philippine Eagle ).

628.nameOriginDescription: Braviary may be a combination of brave or bravery and aviary . It may also involve eyrie .  Warrgle may be a combination of war or warrior and eagle . It may also involve warble , a sound a bird makes.

629.nameOriginDescription: Vullaby may be a combination of vulture and lullaby (which are often sung to children) or baby .  Valchai may be a combination of vulture and child .

630.nameOriginDescription: Mandibuzz may be a combination of mandible or mandil (Spanish for apron) and buzzard .  Vulgina may be a combination of vulture or vulgar and regina (Latin and Italian for queen).

631.nameOriginDescription: Kuitaran may be a combination of 蟻食 arikui (anteater) and anteater or tatara (a kind of furnace), and possibly a play on 食い足らん kuitaran (has not eaten enough).

632.nameOriginDescription: Aiant may be a combination of アイアン aian (iron) and ant .

633.nameOriginDescription: Monozu may be a combination of mono- (prefix meaning one) and 頭 zu (head).

634.nameOriginDescription: Dihead may be a combination of di- (Greek prefix for two) or 二 ji (two) and head .

635.nameOriginDescription: Sazandora may be a combination of 三 san (three), 残忍 zannin (brutal) or 残酷 zankoku (cruel), and dragon or hydra .

636.nameOriginDescription: Merlarva may be a combination of めらめら meramera (onomatopoeia for flaring) and larva .

637.nameOriginDescription: Ulgamoth may be a combination of ウルカヌス Urukanusu ( Vulcanus ), 蛾 ga (moth), and moth .

638.nameOriginDescription: Cobalion and Cobalon may be combinations of cobalt (referring to the metal and the color of cobalt blue ) and stallion or champion .

639.nameOriginDescription: Terrakion may be a combination of terra (Latin for earth) or terracotta (a clay -based material, as well as its respective color), takin , and champion .

640.nameOriginDescription: Virizion may be a combination of viridian (a bluish-green color) or viridis (Latin for green) and champion .

641.nameOriginDescription: Tornadus and Tornelos may be a combination of tornado and Aeolus (ruler of the winds in Greek mythology ; also spelled Αἴολος Aiolos ).

642.nameOriginDescription: Thundurus may be derived from thunderous and possibly Aeolus (ruler of the winds in Greek mythology ).  Voltolos may be a combination of volt and Αἴολος Aiolos (Greek name for Aeolus).

643.nameOriginDescription: Reshiram is derived from 白 shiro (white). Ken Sugimori has also stated that Re was used because it was a softer sound than Zekrom 's Ze , as Reshiram is a less physically powerful character. [ 1 ]

644.nameOriginDescription: Zekrom is derived from 黒 kuro (black). Ken Sugimori has also stated that Ze was used because it was a harder, stronger sound than Reshiram 's Re , and Zekrom is a "powerful, strong character." [ 1 ]

645.nameOriginDescription: Landorus and Landlos may be a combination of land and Aeolus (ruler of the winds in Greek mythology ; also spelled Αἴολος Aiolos ).

646.nameOriginDescription: Kyurem may be derived from 急冷 kyūrei (rapid cooling), グレイ gurei (gray), 冷 rei (cold), 零 rei (zero), or an anagram of ゆき (雪 yuki , snow), and 無 mu (nothing). Rem may also mimic the rom of Zekrom and the ram of Reshiram .

647.nameOriginDescription: Keldeo may be a combination of kelpie (a water horse from Celtic folklore), kelda ( Old Norse for well or spring), and rodeo (a sport involving skills with horses, cows, and other livestock). It may also involve dio (Italian for god).

648.nameOriginDescription: Meloetta may be a combination of melody , pirouette (a type of movement in ballet), operetta , and the Italian feminine diminutive suffix -etta .  Aria is a term now used almost exclusively to describe a self-contained piece for one voice usually with orchestral accompaniment , and is commonly used in opera .

649.nameOriginDescription: Genesect may be a combination of gene , genetics , genome , or genesis ; and insect .

650.nameOriginDescription: Harimaron may be a combination of 蝟 harinezumi (hedgehog), 針 hari (needle), and marron (French for chestnut).

651.nameOriginDescription: Hariborg may be a combination of 蝟 harinezumi (hedgehog), 防具 bōgu (armor), and bogue (French for chestnut shell).

652.nameOriginDescription: Chesnaught may be a combination of chestnut and juggernaut , knight , or dreadnought .  Brigarron may be a combination of brigandine and marron (French for chestnut).

980.nameOriginDescription: Dooh may be a combination of 土 do (earth or ground), 毒 doku (poison), 王 ō (king), オオサンショウウオ ōsanshōuo ( Japanese giant salamander ), and ヌオー Nuoh (Quagsire).

981.nameOriginDescription: Rikikirin may be derived from 力 riki (power) and 麒麟 kirin (giraffe) with the name being an anagram of キリンリキ Kirinriki (Girafarig). It not being a palindrome may reflect that Farigiraf’s tail now surrounds its head.

982.nameOriginDescription: Nokokocchi may be derived from a partial repetition of ノコッチ Nokocchi (Dunsparce), for the same reasons mentioned above.

983.nameOriginDescription: Dodogezan may be a combination of ど do (very much), 土下座 dogeza (kneeling down on the ground), and 斬 zan (to cut or slay). ドゲザン Dogezan is also the Japanese name for its signature move , Kowtow Cleave .

984.nameOriginDescription: Idainakiba can be taken literally as 偉大な牙 idai na kiba (great tusk).

985.nameOriginDescription: Sakebushippo can be taken literally as 叫ぶ尻尾 sakebu shippo (screaming tail).

986.nameOriginDescription: Araburutake can be taken literally as 荒ぶる茸 araburu take (savage mushroom).

987.nameOriginDescription: Habatakukami can be taken literally as 羽ばたく髪 habataku kami (fluttering hair).

988.nameOriginDescription: Chiwohauhane can be taken literally as 地を這う羽 chi o hau hane (wings slithering on the ground).

989.nameOriginDescription: Sunanokegawa can be taken literally as 砂の毛皮 suna no kegawa (sandy fur).

990.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunowadachi can be taken literally as 鉄の轍 tetsu no wadachi (iron treads).

991.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunotsutsumi can be taken literally as 鉄の包み tetsu no tsutsumi (iron bundle).

992.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunokaina can be taken literally as 鉄の腕 tetsu no kaina (iron arms).

993.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunokoube can be taken literally as 鉄の首 tetsu no kōbe (iron head).

994.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunodokuga can be taken literally as 鉄の毒蛾 tetsu no dokuga (iron venomous moth).

995.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunoibara can be taken literally as 鉄の棘 tetsu no ibara (iron thorn).

996.nameOriginDescription: Sebie may be a combination of 背 se (back) and 冷え hie (coldness).

997.nameOriginDescription: Segohru may be a combination of 背 se (back) and 凍る kōru (freeze).

998.nameOriginDescription: Seglaive may be a combination of 背 se (back) and glaive (referring to a polearm weapon with origins in Europe, or short swords such as the Gladius ).

999.nameOriginDescription: Collecurei may be a combination of collect , 霊 rei (spirit), and a pun on the phrase これくれ kore kure ("Give me this").

1000.nameOriginDescription: Surfugo may be a combination of surf , 富豪 fugō (wealthy person), gold , and possibly go (as in Pokémon GO).

1001.nameOriginDescription: Wo-Chien may be a combination of 蝸 / 蜗 wō (Chinese for snail) and 簡 / 简 jiǎn (Chinese for bamboo slips). The name is formatted in Wade–Giles , a romanization system used in the Anglosphere for most of the 20th century.  Chionjen may be a combination of 蟲 / 虫 chóng (Chinese for bug) and 簡 / 简 jiǎn (Chinese for bamboo slips).

1002.nameOriginDescription: Chien-Pao and Paojian may be a combination of 劍 / 剑 jiàn (Chinese for sword) or 寶劍 / 宝剑 bǎojiàn (Chinese for treasure sword) and 豹 bào (Chinese for leopard). The English name is formatted in Wade–Giles , a romanization system used in the Anglosphere for most of the 20th century.

1003.nameOriginDescription: Ting-Lu and Dinlu may be a combination of 鼎 dǐng (ancient Chinese cauldron) and 鹿 lù (Chinese for deer). The English name is formatted in Wade–Giles , a romanization system used in the Anglosphere for most of the 20th century.

1004.nameOriginDescription: Chi-Yu may be a combination of 鯽魚 / 鲫鱼 jìyú (Chinese for crucian carp , from which goldfish are domesticated) and 玉 yù (Chinese for jade). The name is formatted in Wade–Giles , a romanization system used in the Anglosphere for most of the 20th century.  Yiyui may be a combination of 魚 / 鱼 yú (Chinese for fish) and 玉 yù (Chinese for jade). Both /i/ and /ui/ are common approximates of the close front rounded vowel (represented as -ü- or yu- in pinyin , pronounced like French u or German ü) in languages where the vowel is not present.

1005.nameOriginDescription: Todorokutsuki can be taken literally as 轟く月 todoroku tsuki (roaring moon).

1006.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunobujin can be taken literally as 鉄の武人 tetsu no bujin (iron warrior).

1007.nameOriginDescription: Koraidon may be a combination of 古来 korai or 古代 kodai (ancient), ライド raido (ride), and dragon , don (Spanish for lord), or -don (common suffix in dinosaur names derived from the Ancient Greek word for tooth).  Tsubasano'ou, its alternate name in Japanese, can be taken literally as 翼の王 tsubasa no ō (winged king).

1008.nameOriginDescription: Miraidon may be a combination of 未来 mirai (future), ライド raido (ride), and dragon , don (Spanish for lord), or -don (common suffix in dinosaur names derived from the Ancient Greek word for tooth).  Tetsuno'orochi, its alternate name in Japanese, can be taken literally as 鉄の大蛇 tetsu no orochi (iron serpent).

1009.nameOriginDescription: Uneruminamo can be taken literally as うねる水面 uneru minamo (undulating water's surface).

1010.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunoisaha can be taken literally as 鉄の斑葉 tetsu no isaha (iron mottled leaves).

1011.nameOriginDescription: Kamicchu may be a combination of 果 ka (fruit), 花蜜 kamitsu (nectar), 虫 chū (bug; worm), and カジッチュ Kajicchu (Applin).

1012.nameOriginDescription: Poltchageist may be a combination of poltergeist and 抹茶 matcha , following the same naming pattern as Polteageist .  Chadeath may be a combination of 抹茶 matcha , death , and ポットデス Potdeath (Polteageist), as well as a pun on 茶です cha desu ("It's tea").

1013.nameOriginDescription: Sinistcha may be a combination of sinister and 抹茶 matcha , following the same naming pattern as Sinistea .  Yabasocha may be a combination of やばい yabai (dangerous; terrible), ヤバチャ Yabacha (Sinistea), and 粗茶 socha (low grade tea, coarse tea).

1014.nameOriginDescription: Iineinu may be a combination of いいね ii ne (interjection to express approval) and 犬 inu (dog).

1015.nameOriginDescription: Mashimashira may be a combination of 増し mashi (better, improving) and 猿 mashira (archaic word for monkey or ape).

1016.nameOriginDescription: Kichikigisu may be a combination of 吉 kichi (fortune) and 雉子 kigisu (archaic reading of pheasant).

1017.nameOriginDescription: Ogerpon may be derived from ogre and ponkan or dekopon (varieties of orange), as well as ～ぽん -pon , a cutesy suffix applied to names as a form of endearment.

1018.nameOriginDescription: Briduras may be derived from bridge , ジュラルドン Duraludon , and ソーラス -saurus (Greek-derived suffix for dinosaur names).

1019.nameOriginDescription: Kamitsuorochi may be a combination of 果 ka (fruit), 花蜜 kamitsu (nectar), and 八岐大蛇 Yamata no Orochi .

1020.nameOriginDescription: Ugatsuhomura can be taken literally as 穿つ炎 ugatsu homura (piercing flame).

1021.nameOriginDescription: Takeruraiko can be taken as 猛る雷鼓 takeru raiko (furious thunderclap). It may also come from Raikou .

1022.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunoiwao can be taken literally as 鉄の巌 tetsu no iwao (iron boulder).

1023.nameOriginDescription: Tetsunokashira can be taken literally as 鉄の頭 tetsu no kashira (iron head; iron leader).

1024.nameOriginDescription: Terapagos may be a combination of Terastal , terrapin , and galápagos (a Spanish word for turtles, most recognizable because of the Galápagos Islands ).

1025.nameOriginDescription: Momowarou may be a combination of 桃太郎 Momotarō , 桃 momo (peach), and 悪し waroshi (bad or inferior; the classical Japanese form of 悪い warui ) or 和郎 warō (boy).
